Dear professor,

    As we discussed, the past week I was focusing on MH-within-Gibbs sampling with Gaussian mixture model. I also implemented a demo for better understanding of the main ideas of it.

    Following is the main steps of Gibbs sampling:


  • Step 0:  Initialize mixture parameters () , Gaussian mixture weights of k-components (P) and other parameters.
  • Step 1.1: During each iteration,:
    • Step 1.1: first of all we need to generate the membership matix for every observation using Gaussian distribution probability density function (PDF) with the parameters generated at the previous iteration. In my implementation I just allocate an observation with certain component if the membership probability is the highest one.
    • With the membership matrix in hand, just sum the matrix then we will have the Nj (j = 1,...k).
    • Step 1.2: Since , so we assume P obeys Dirichlet distribution and generate new mixture weights P' from
    • Using MH algorithm to generate mixture parameters.

    From my understanding, the main problem of Gibbs sampling is the difficulty of finding out the posterior distribution of mixture parameters. In order to solve this problem, Metropolis-hastings algorithm is a good alternative :


  • Step 0: Since P' has been generated before, so in the MH algorithm we only discuss how to generate mixture parameters () . Specifically for Gaussian mixture model, the mixture parameters are means () and variance ()
  • Step 1: For each iteration:
    • Step 1.1: Generate new means () and variance () using proposal distributions. In my implementation, for simplification purpose, I selected normal distributions as proposal distributions for both  and . For further improvements, I will consider to use log-normal distribution or inverse Gamma distribution as the proposals.
    • Step 1.2: Calculate acceptance ration r to decide whether we accept the generated new parameters or not. Here the f(x|,) is the known Gaussian mixture PDF and based on Bayesian rules, (,)=( | )*() , we assume  and  are independant so  (,)=()*(). The same situiation for the proposal distribution.
    • Generate a random value [0,1] and compare it with acceptance ration r. If r < , the newly generated parameters will be accepted as the initial parameters for next iteration. Otherwise, keep using the old parameters.
  • After T iterations, calculate acceptance ration by calculate accepted jumps / total jumps, draw the jump trace and density regions for each component of the GMM.
Results:
    Tested my demo with different initial parameters and different observation clusters and components.The clustering results are not good enough maybe the proposal distributions are not fit so if the observations are far away from the initial mixture parameters,the acceptance ration of jumps will be low.


Problems:
  1. During every iteration, we need to calculate probabilities using f(x|,)  for all the observations in order to generate the acceptance ration r. Theoretically it's correct but in practice I found it's infeasible to multiple many fractions together (the result will always be - Inf) . In order to make my demo works, I change the prod to sum. I understand the purpose of calculating probabilities here is to evaluate fitness of newly generated mixture parameters but I'm afraid this change will affect the accuracy so I would like to know if you could give me some hint of how to solve this problem?
  2. I noticed there are many candidates for the proposal distribution (log-normal, Gamma, Inverse-Gamma or adaptive Gaussian mixture etc,.) and I got confused about which one I should select and why, could you give me some advises about how to better understand those?
     Thank you and I'm looking forward to meeting you tomorrow.

Best regards,
Shuai
